accesses.lakeAccessComments: Fishing pier on west central point.

surveys.narrative: Pumpkinseed and bluegill are present in very low numbers, black bullhead in average numbers and northern pike in high numbers. Northern pike present, are, for the most part, naturally reproduced fish. Bluegill numbers have been drastically reduced from levels found in earlier surveys (1970, 1975). One possible reason is undetected winterkill conditions. Largemouth bass and bluegill young of the year were found in shoreline seining.

The fish population of this lake has primarily consisted of Northern Pike (NOP), Bluegill (BLG) and Largemouth Bass (LMB). Recent management efforts on Holland Lake have focused on attempting to establish a 2 story fishery that supports the periodic stocking of stream trout species. Two adult Brown Trout (BNT) averaging 21.32" TL and 4.08 pounds were captured during this survey. These fish were surplus brood stock that had been culled from the state hatchery system and stocked the previous Fall to provide a put-and-take fishery. Northern Pike (NOP) were sampled below the median levels for abundance and above the median level for mean weight in 2007. The average size NOP captured was approximately 22.6 inches and 2.8 pounds. Bluegill (BLG) were sampled in the highest abundance of any species during this survey. The trap net catch rate for BLG was the highest ever recorded for this lake, but no individuals larger than 5.7 inches in length were captured. The average size for sampled BLG is 4.5 inches and 0.05 pounds (19.5 fish/lb). Growth rates for NOP and BLG were found to be below average.

The fish population of this lake primarily consists of Northern Pike, Bluegill and Largemouth Bass. Recent management efforts on Holland Lake have focused on attempting to establish a 2 story fishery that supports the periodic stocking of stream trout species. Brown Trout have been observed in previous surveys but none were captured during this survey. When present these fish are surplus brood stock culled from the state hatchery system and stocked in the fall to provide a put-and-take winter fishery. Northern Pike were sampled well above the median levels for abundance and at the median level for mean weight in 2013. The average size NOP captured was approximately 20.78 inches and 2.78 pounds. Bluegills were sampled in the highest abundance of any species during this survey. The trap net catch rate for Bluegill was the highest ever recorded for this lake, but the average size is small with only 23 individuals out of total of 397 (6%) larger than 6.0 inches in length being captured. Growth rates for Northern Pike and Bluegill were found to be below average when compared to statewide averages. Other panfish seen during this survey were Pumpkinseed and Hybrid Sunfish, each of which was also sampled in their highest abundance ever. These other panfish were found to be small in size and have poor to slow growth for lakes similar to Holland Lake. Six Largemouth Bass were observed in the sampling gear, these fish had an average length of 12.36 inches and an average weight of 1.42 lbs. Some other fish seen in during this survey were Black Crappie which were observed in low numbers and were of small size and Green Sunfish which were also not very numerous and small in size.

Northern pike population is just a little above the state and local medians in size and number. The walleye population is suspected to be very small, just what fishermen may have stocked from surrounding lakes. The bluegill population is small in size and number. No crappies were found. Locals report a very nice population of largemouth bass, with 3 and 4 lb. fish commonly caught.

White sucker and pumpkinseed are present in numbers and pounds per set below the statewide median. Northern pike and black bullhead are present in numbers and pounds per set above the median. While bluegill numbers are above the statewide median, the weight is below it.

Fish numbers in the 1995 survey were low. Fish aged were small and growth was slow. Bluegill, pumpkinseed, green, and hybrid sunfish were captured, with most under 6 inches in length. Black and white crappie were captured for the first time in the lake, with no fish over 9 inches. Three largemouth were sampled, one of acceptable size to anglers. One black bullhead was captured, down from previous nettings.

Northern pike were sampled in below average abundance - a significant reduction from previous investigations. This may be a result of lower water levels as a result of recent drought conditions. Growth of pike was average for the area. Golden shiners were abundant. Bluegill were sampled in average numbers, but were of small average size. Bluegill abundance has remained stable for several investigations. Hybrid sunfish were sampled at higher than state and local median levels. Black bullheads were sampled at above local median levels and were small in size. Higher numbers of small largemouth bass were sampled in gillnets. Three largemouth bass year classes were sampled which exhibited average growth for the region.

The fish population of Holland Lake has primarily consisted of northern pike, bluegill, and largemouth bass. Northern pike were sampled above median levels for abundance in gill nets and at the highest catch rate ever observed. The average northern pike sampled was 22.24 inches in length and 2.95 pounds. Thirty-one percent of the gill net sample of northern pike was 26.0 inches or larger. Overall growth rates were near average for this species. Bluegill and pumpkinseed sunfish were sampled above median levels for abundance in trap nets and at the highest catch rates ever observed. The average size of sampled bluegill was 4.9 inches in length and 0.08 pounds. Only 8.1% of all bluegill captured were 6.0 inches or longer. Pumpkinseed sunfish averaged only 4.22 inches in length. Two small largemouth bass yearlings and no adults were sampled during this assessment. Recent management efforts for this lake have attempted to develop a two-story fish population by stocking brown and rainbow trout. Adult brown trout broodstock culls have been stocked here since 1998. Yearling rainbow and brown trout have also been stocked since 2000. No trout were captured during the 2001 netting assessment.
